{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512756"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:00:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:00:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11945"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11945"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.21,0.13,0.45,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116313"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11945"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98309"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2175"},{"type":"tags","id":"2583"},{"type":"tags","id":"3990"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4662"},{"type":"tags","id":"4812"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49919"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116313"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-week history of fluidy vaginal discharge, intermittent vaginal spotting and intermittent deep dyspareunia. She has no abdominal pain at. She has not experienced any fevers or urinary symptoms. She has had one sexual partner for the last five months and she takes the combined oral contraceptive pill appropriately with no missed doses. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications other than her contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Bimanual examination shows no adnexal or uterine tenderness and no palpable masses. Speculum examination reveals a slightly reddened cervix with a small amount of mucus and thin, whitish discharge at the os. Urine pregnancy test is negative. You collect samples and have received the below results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocervical swab\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChlamydia trachomatis: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh vaginal swab MCS:\u003C/strong\u003E Normal vaginal flora\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical co-test\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV 16: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV 18: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV non 16/18: Not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiquid based cytology: Negative for intraepithelial lesion or malignancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat endocervical swab for chlamydia, gonorrhoea and trichomonas in 14 days","Transvaginal ultrasound scan","Oral metronidazole for 7 days","Endocervical swab for mycoplasma genitalium","Clotrimazole pessary for 5 days"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms of cervicitis (vaginal discharge, spotting, and deep dyspareunia) but initial testing for common sexually transmitted infections (STIs) has been negative. In this scenario, the most appropriate next step is to perform an endocervical swab for \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma genitalium\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E (\u003Cem\u003EM. genitalium\u003C/em\u003E), which is an increasingly recognised cause of urethritis, cervicitis and pelvic inflammatory disease. In Australia, the prevalence of \u003Cem\u003EM. genitalium\u003C/em\u003E is estimated to be 1-2% in the general population and up to 10% in high-risk groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating the endocervical swab for chlamydia, gonorrhoea and trichomonas in 14 days\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this point. The initial tests were performed correctly using endocervical swabs, which are a highly sensitive method for detecting these pathogens. A repeat test would be indicated if testing was done within 14 days of a new sexual contact, or if there is a high suspicion of a false negative without other explanation of her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransvaginal ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step at this stage. While it can be useful for evaluating pelvic structures, the patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings primarily suggest an infectious process rather than a structural abnormality. If symptoms persist despite exclusion or treatment of potential infections, imaging may be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat bacterial vaginosis and trichomoniasis. However, the high vaginal swab showed normal vaginal flora, and trichomonas was not detected on the endocervical swab. Therefore, empiric treatment with metronidazole is not appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClotrimazole pessary\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat vaginal candidiasis. However, the patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are not typical of candidiasis, and the high vaginal swab did not show evidence of yeast overgrowth. Therefore, antifungal treatment is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EM genitalium\u003C/em\u003E is an important cause of cervicitis that is not detected by routine STI testing. It requires specific nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT) for diagnosis. This can be performed on either urine samples or endocervical swabs, with swabs generally being more sensitive. Given the patient\u0027s persistent symptoms and negative results for other common pathogens, testing for \u003Cem\u003EM genitalium\u003C/em\u003E is the most appropriate next step. If positive, it can be treated with appropriate antibiotics, typically doxycycline followed by azithromycin, or moxifloxacin if there is macrolide resistance or if pelvic inflammatory disease is present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mycoplasma genitalium is an important cause of cervicitis and should be considered when other common pathogens have been ruled out.","Mycoplasma genitalium can be detected in both urine and swab samples using nucleic acid amplification tests."],"references":["DiMarco DE, Urban MA, McGowan JP, et al. Mycoplasma genitalium Management in Adults. Baltimore (MD): Johns Hopkins University; 2022 Mar. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK583532/","Australian STI Management Guidelines: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/mycoplasma-genitalium/","Htaik K, Vodstrcil LA, Plummer EL, Sfameni AM, Machalek DA, Manhart LE, et al. Systematic review and meta-analysis of the association between Mycoplasma genitalium and Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID). Clinical infectious diseases/Clinical infectious diseases (Online University of Chicago Press). 2024 Jun 7. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/cid/advance-article/doi/10.1093/cid/ciae295/7689270"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98309"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11945"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98309"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T12:17:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T12:17:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4541"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116313"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"dat